<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Carillion response to the Communities and Local Government Committee Inquiry into Local Government Procurement</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from Carillion (LPG 55)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion welcomes this opportunity to respond to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Communities and Local Government Committee’s Inquiry into Local Government Procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In order to put our comments into context it may be useful to outline briefly our role as a key partner for local authorities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">'s leading support services companies with a substantial portfolio of Public Private Partnership projects and extensive construction capabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Group has annual revenue of around £4.4 billion, employs in the region of 40,000 people and operates across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the Middle East and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Canada</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion works with local government to provide a full range of integrated support services including highway maintenance, facilities management, property and estates management and energy services.  We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have worked</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with Birmingham City Council to construct th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e world’s largest public library,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, under a separate contract, we are delivering </span><a href="http://www.birminghamenergysavers.org.uk/index.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Birmingham Energy Savers</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity’s flagship Green Deal energy efficiency programme.  In 2012 we signed a £500 million contract with Oxfordshire County Council to deliver fully integrated and consolidated property and facilities management services, the first initiative of its kind, which will save the Council up to £550,000 each year over the next decade.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion also has a strong presence in Greater Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and offers a range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capabilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public sector partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a joint venture partner with Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council providing a range of services and significant local investment, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a partner with Rochdale MBC delivering new and refurbished schools in the Borough.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Additionally, we have been selected as one of three preferred bidders on the Manchester Airport Capital Delivery Framework, which will bring vital economic regeneration to the area, and are working with the Association of Greater Manchester Authorities (AGMA) to deliver “Get me Toasty,” a pilot energy saving scheme, which will help combat fuel poverty for up to 3,000 households.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have used our private sector experience in local government to help achieve better outcomes, for example supporting community engagement in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by creating award-winning community gardens and opening up our facilities for community use.  Our legacy strategy for Birmingham City Council demonstrates our continuing commitment to the area – we have created 250 local employment opportunities, 278 apprenticeships and we have worked with local SMEs.  Similarly, for our contract with Oxfordshire County Council we have committed to holding almost 600 local education engagement sessions, 180 back to work trials, 400 hours of SME or third sector monitoring and a commitment to 60% local spend, which we hope to exceed to reach 70%.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For further information about Carillion and our work with local government or apprentices, please visit our website: </span><a name="_Hlt224127153"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><a href="http://www.carillionplc.com/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.carillionplc.com/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><a href="http://www.carillionplc.com/our-markets/local-authorities.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.carillionplc.com/our-markets/local-authorities.aspx</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Response to individual questions:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? To what extent are local authorities achieving the involvement of local residents in delivering value for money? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion believes that local government procurement is focused on a combination of value for money, local economic benefits and social and environmental objectives.  Incorporation of the Social Value Act is usually included within the tender process and helps to achieve social and environmental objectives.  Partnership agreements between local government and the private sector promote trust and openness in procurement, aligning both parties more closely to achieve the stated objectives in collaboration.  However, there can remain barriers to delivering added value to contracts if value for money is perceived to equate to lowest cost.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion is committed to involving local residents when delivering contracts on behalf of local authorities and this is integral to our vision of successful delivery.  When working for local authorities we become embedded within communities, actively engaging residents through multiple channels, including working with schools, civil society groups and by employing dedicated community liaison managers.  It is not, however, clear what role local authorities currently play in involving residents as active participants in delivering value for money – achieving this outcome is perhaps linked to improved public engagement with local democracy, which can be supported through initiatives such as Cooperative Councils.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is evidence that local authorities are developing long-term relationships with contractors, which evolve to fit local authorities’ changing circumstances.  Different types of partnering arrangements that derive from a single procurement type such as property or construction but subsequently broaden in scope are becoming increasingly common.  An example Carillion is familiar with would be Local Education Partnerships that have developed into Strategic Property Partnerships.  However, the success of such partnerships is varied depending on the willingness and commitment of both or all parties to collaborate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Government is changing to take better advantage of joint procurement opportunities; however there is still room for improvement on this front.  We would highlight the AGMA combined authority model as an example of successful formalised joint procurement arrangements; however in some other joint procurement scenarios there is perhaps insufficient groundwork done before procurement stage to secure full collaboration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives? More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion believes local authorities should be prepared to undertake open dialogue with interested experts from both the public and private sector through soft market testing or opportunities for collaborative communication.  Early commissioning of works with specialist companies can help to define clear briefs, expectations and outcomes regarding social value from the outset.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local government understanding of its market is variable and it is difficult to definitively assess whether this works overall.  Generally it may be fair to expect that larger local authorities have a better understanding due to their greater strategic influence; however this is not necessarily the case.  As indicated above, collaboration is the key to achieving better shared outcomes and ensuring obstacles can be addressed at an early stage.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greater regional collaboration through pre-procurement commitments and strategy will inevitably drive greater private sector commitment and investment but local authorities are not all equally ready to work in this manner – clear direction from leadership is required, which must be actively supported by all levels throughout the organisation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the main, local authorities have a good understanding and management of risk though we are aware of examples where risk has been misunderstood and allocation of risk has consequently been shared inappropriately between client and contractor.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that most local authority clients are able to adapt to change and challenging circumstances; however, there is more scope for the private sector to be flexible on long term contracts as with shorter term contracts there is less manoeuvrability to achieve an acceptable return on investment, which will ultimately drive savings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How is regularity and propriety of procurement secured and are the arrangements for detecting and addressing impropriety and fraud effective? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion believes that arrangements for securing propriety are generally adequate.  Often bidders must sign agreements committing to meet specific expectations to avoid impropriety.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">local authority procurement fully transparent, audited effectively and does it provide appropriate mechanisms for redress? Specifically, are the arrangements for securing the accountability of procured services and goods to local authorities and local residents adequate and effective? More specifically, to what extent are local authorities able to provide assurance to central government that value for money (in the broadest sense of the term) is delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carillion agrees that mechanisms for redress are usually explicit and clear within the bid documentation from the outset.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>